Welcome to The CBA Guide. This Guide is meant to serve as an in-depth reference guide to the NBA‚Äôs CBA and Salary Cap rules.

You will find the all-in-one [Master Guide](#top) below. If you prefer a section-by-section breakdown of the Guide, you can [start here](https://cbaguide.com/section/).

**Searching The Guide**

If you‚Äôre looking for a specific term, you can enter it in the search bar above (or hit \[Command\] + F and search through the entire Guide).

**Citations**

The majority of The Guide has citations to the sections and page numbers of the CBA. If you hover your mouse over the paragraph , and you see a bubble appear (or if mobile, tap on the paragraph to make the bubble appear). Click the bubble for the citation. Example below:



**Resources**

The CBA Guide includes additional resources, including the following:

* [2025-26 Salary Cap Amounts](https://cbaguide.com/resources/amounts/);
* [Rookie Salary Scale](https://cbaguide.com/resources/rookiescale/);
* [Minimum Salary Scale](https://cbaguide.com/resources/minimumscale/);
* [Historical Salary Cap Thresholds](https://cbaguide.com/resources/caphistory/);
* [The Over 38 Calculator](https://cbaguide.com/resources/over38calculator/).

Exhibit 1 identifies the different Compensation and Payment Arrangements in the Contract:

1. [Base Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/basecompensation/);
2. [Deferred Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#deferred);
3. [Payment Schedule](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#schedule);
4. [Signing Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#signingbonus);
5. [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/);
6. [Options and Early Termination Options (ETO‚Äôs)](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/options/);
7. [Insurance Premium Reimbursements](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/#premium);
8. [No-Trade Provisions](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/traderules/#notrade).

Below are the different Contract Types a Player can sign:

1. [Standard NBA Contract](#standard);
2. [Two-Way Contract](#twoway);
3. [Ten-Day Contract](#tenday);
4. [Rest-of-Season Contract](#rest);
5. [Exhibit 10 Contract](#exhibit10);
6. [Exhibit 9 Contract](#exhibit9);
7. [Rookie Scale Contract](#rookie).

**üèÄ** **Martin Exemplifies the Cycle of Contract Types for Burgeoning NBA Player**  

Tyrese Martin of the Brooklyn Nets provides a timeline how the different Contract Types can work.  

9/20/2024 ‚Äì Signs an Exhibit 10 Contract with the Nets as a UFA.  

10/19/2024 ‚Äì Exhibit 10 Contract is converted to a Two-Way Contract for the 2024-25 Season.  

2/20/2025 ‚Äì During the 2024-25 Season, Martin‚Äôs Two-Way Contract is converted to a 2-Year Rest-of-Season Contract with a Team Option for the 2025-26 Season.  

6/28/25 ‚Äì Nets exercise Martin‚Äôs Team Option for the 2025-26 Season.

If the Conversion Option is exercised by the Team:

1. Becomes a [Two-Way Contract](#twoway);
2. Paid Two-Way Salary;
3. Exhibit 10 Bonus is rescinded;
4. Conversion Protection Amount is triggered;
5. All other terms remain in Contract.

After Conversion, it can be converted _back_ to a Standard NBA Contract via the Standard NBA Contract Conversion Option contained in the Two-Way.

### Timing

An Exhibit 10 must be converted to a Two-Way Contract prior to the first day of the Regular Season.

### Unsigned Second Round Picks

If the Drafting Team signed a Second Round Pick to a [Required Tender](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/draftrules/) and subsequently waived the Player, the Drafting Team still has exclusive Two-Way rights to the Draftee until the Subsequent Draft.

Therefore, the Non-Drafting Team Signing him to a Standard Contract can‚Äôt convert him via Exhibit 10 to a Two-Way Contract because it will breach the exclusivity.

### Required Terms

Below are the required terms if a Contract includes an Exhibit 9:

1. Must be for 1 Season in length;
2. Provides for [Minimum Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/contractlimitations/) (with no bonuses of any kind) or a [Two-Way Salary](#twoway);
3. Does not provide for [Compensation Protection](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/) of any kind.

Below are the different types of Compensation (click to see rules applicable to each type):

1. [Base Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/basecompensation/);
2. [Regular Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/regularsalary/);
3. [Salary](https://cbaguide.com/salary/);
4. [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/terms/incentivecompensation/);
5. [Signing Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#signingbonus).

The CBA defines **Salary** as the following:

### Include:

1. [Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/) earned by a Player with respect to such Season;
2. [Retired Player Payments](https://cbaguide.com/governance/circumvention/#retired).

### Exclude:

1. [Unlikely Bonuses](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/#performance);
2. Benefits.

### Adjustments

Make adjustments to Salary if the below circumstances are applicable:

1. [Deferred Compensation](#deferred);
2. [The ‚ÄúOver 38 Rule‚Äù](#over38);
3. [Signing Bonuses](#signingbonuses);
4. [Trade Bonuses](#tradebonuses);
5. [1-Year Minimum Contracts](#oneyear);
6. [Restricted Free Agency (the ‚ÄúGilbert Arenas Provision‚Äù)](#gilbert);
7. [Excluded International Player Payments (EIPPA)](#eippa);
8. [Incentive Compensation](#incentive);
9. [Suspensions](#incentive);
10. [Loans](#loans).

Below are the provisions in the CBA applying Regular Salary:

1. [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/) Limits;
2. [Free Agent Cap Holds](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/teamsalary/#capholds);
3. [Annual Increases and Decreases](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/contractlimitations/#increases) (separate from Incentive Compensation);
4. [Bird Rights](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/#bird) Limits (separate from Likely/Unlikely Bonuses).

Base Compensation

Below are the provisions in the CBA applying Base Compensation:

1. [Advance](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#advance) Limits;
2. [Compensation Protection](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/);
3. [Minimum Contracts](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/contractlimitations/);
4. [Two-Way Contracts](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/contracttypes/#twoway);
5. [Maximum Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/contractlimitations/) (last type of Compensation reduced);
6. Reduction in Pay Due to [Suspension](https://cbaguide.com/governance/conduct/);
7. Proration Calculation of [Signing Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#signingbonus) when Calculating Salary;
8. Deduction in relation to [Loans](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#loans);
9. Calculation of [Trade Salary](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/tradesalary/);
10. Pro rata reduction of Compensation Protection in a [Buyout](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/waivers/#buyout);
11. [Rookie Scale](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/draftpicks/) Salary Amounts;
12. Qualifying Offer /Offer Sheet Requirements in [Restricted Free Agency](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/rfa/);
13. Partial [Waiver](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/waivers/#partial) Claim Obligations;
14. [Trade Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/tradebonus/) Limits;
15. [Set-Off](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/waivers/#setoff) Calculation;
16. [Stretching](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/#deadsalary) of Protected Compensation.

Incentive Compensation

**Incentive Compensation** is the all-encompassing definition for three types of incentives permitted in Contracts:

1. Performance Bonuses (Likely or Unlikely);
2. Physical/Academic Achievements;
3. Promotional Appearances.

Performance Bonuses have the following requirements:

1. Incentive must provide for positive achievement;
2. Must be based on specific numerical benchmarks or ‚ÄúGenerally Recognized League Honors‚Äù;
3. Must be based on official league statistics as published on NBA.com;
4. Cannot relate to being on a team‚Äôs roster by a specific date or active for a certain amount of games.

**üí°** While Bonuses cannot be contingent on staying on the roster by a certain date, Compensation Protection can, and often does, contain such a contingency.

**üèÄ** **Example Provided in CBA**  
The CBA contains a specific example explaining criteria types permitted and prohibited: If the Bonus is for the player exceeding 80% free throw shooting, it is permitted. However, if the Bonus is for the Player improving his free throw shooting percentage over the prior Season, it is prohibited.

The Team can still pay the Player a bonus linked to attendance when the Player did not attend under three circumstances:

1. Waiver ‚Äì The Team Waives the Player‚Äôs requirement to attend;
2. Substitution ‚Äì In lieu of the specified services, the Player trains/plays with his national team during the offseason;
3. Illness/Injury ‚Äì The player is unable to perform.

Compensation Protection

Generally, Contracts are not required to guarantee any [Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/) owed.

**Compensation Protection** can be added to a Contract to guarantee all or a portion of a Player‚Äôs [Base Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/basecompensation/) if the Contract is terminated prior to the expiration of its term.

There are different types of Compensation Protection:

1. Lack of Skill;
2. Basketball-Related Injury;
3. Injury/Illness;
4. Mental Disability;
5. Death.

For categories 2 through 5, the Team must not have procured an insurance policy for the Player‚Äôs benefit.

**üí°** The majority of NBA Contracts are guaranteed. When guaranteed, they are most commonly guaranteed for lack of skill and injury/illness.

Compensation Protection may have additional conditions, but only upon the following types of conditions:

1. Increased protection if the Player is not [waived](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/waivers/) by certain dates;
2. Increased protection based upon achievement of Team/Player performance benchmarks or the player‚Äôs physical condition (applying same criterion rules for [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/));
3. Injury-specific conditions ‚Äì Team can carve out specific injuries from the injury protection;
4. Insurance ‚Äì Dependent on the Team‚Äôs ability to obtain insurance, using best efforts, within a specific time, of a certain type/dollar amount.

**üèÄ** **Poeltl‚Äôs Salary Conditional Upon Minutes Played**  
In 2025, Jakob Poeltl signed an Extension through 2029-30\. Each season was fully guaranteed except the 2029-30 season, which had Compensation for $5 million, that would increase based upon the following conditions: Starting in 2026-27, each season Poeltl played 1,400 minutes, the guarantee would increase $5 million. If he played 1,400 minutes and Toronto made the playoffs, the guarantee would increase another $2,433,333

A Player is not entitled to Compensation Protection if the termination of his Contract was based upon the following:

**Activities Terminating Base Compensation**

1. Prohibited activities itemized in Exhibit 12 of Player‚Äôs UPC (which can be modified from Player to Player);
2. Attempted suicide;
3. Intentional self-inflicted injury;
4. Abuse of alcohol;
5. Use of any Prohibited Substance/controlled substance or abuse or prescription drug;
6. Conduct during commission of felony for which he is convicted;
7. Participation in any riot.

**Breach**

If the Player is in material breach of his Contract, he is not entitled to Compensation Protection.

**Procuring Insurance**

If the Player fails to assist in the Team‚Äôs procurement and processing of an insurance policy covering the type of Compensation Protection, then the Compensation Protection is not in effect.

A Signing Bonus can‚Äôt exceed 15% of the Extended Term of the Contract.

If a Signing Bonus is agreed upon in an [Extension](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/extensions/), it cannot be payable until the July 1st of the first year of the [Extension](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/extensions/), _unless_ the Team is below the [Salary Cap](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/).

If the Team is below the Salary Cap:

1. Signing is treated as a **Renegotiate and Extend**;
2. Signing Bonus cannot exceed the [Salary Cap](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/) for existing years;
3. The first Season of the [Extension](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/extensions/) cannot exceed 140% of the [Renegotiated](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/renegotiations/) final Season;
4. Paid in two installments:  
   * First, paid on a day prior to the Extended Term for an amount equal to the portion of the Signing Bonus allocated to the Salary Cap Years covered under the original term;  
   * Second, paid once the Extended Term is in effect, an amount covering the Extended Term.

Below are the limitations for both Team and Player Options:

1. Can only be for 1 Year;
2. [Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/salary/) (less [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/)), Likely Bonuses and Unlikely Bonuses cannot be less than the prior year;
3. All other terms and conditions (including [Compensation Protection](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/)) must remain unchanged from the prior year, other than the Player‚Äôs [Payment Schedule](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/);
4. No Conditions ‚Äì The Option must be a fixed right and not exercised/declined based upon a condition.

The increase/decrease limitations are broken into the following [Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/) types:

1. [Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/salary/), exclusing [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/);
2. [Regular Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/regularsalary/);
3. [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/) ‚Äì Each individual bonus may only be increased/decreased by the applicable limit;  
   * The criteria for earnning any Bonus must also be unchanged from year to year.

**üèÄ** **Explaining How the Rule Works**  
The rule means that you look at increase and decrease limitations within each Compensation type rather than as a whole. Therefore, if a Player receives $10 million in Regular Salary in Year 1 with $2 million in Performance Bonuses with 5% maximum raises, then you apply the 5% to $10 million Regular Salary and 5% to the $2 million Bonuses separately, rather than a combined $12 million.

**üí°** **Why Split Compensation Types for This Limitation?**  
Without splitting Compensation types for the increase/decrease limitations a Team can manipulate Team Salary year to year. For example, a Team can offer $20 million in Base Compensation with $2 million in Unlikely Bonuses (which don‚Äôt count toward the Salary Cap) in Year 1, then in Year 2 increase Regular Salary to $23,100,000 (5% of all Compensation) while dropping Unlikely Bonuses to $0.

Other than finishing an existing Contract, a Player may become a UFA in other ways, including:

1. A Prior Team‚Äôs right to match (‚ÄúROFR Rights‚Äù) are relinquished during [Restricted Free Agency](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/rfa/);
2. Player clears [Waivers](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/waivers/);
3. [Draft Rights](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/draftrules/) are relinquished;
4. Player is [undrafted](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/draftrules/).

While a UFA is free to sign with any Team, each Team is limited by its current financial situation.

Teams can sign a UFA using the following methods:

1. Cap Space;
2. [Salary Cap Exception](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/) available to Sign UFA:  
   * NTMLE ($14,104,000);  
   * TMLE ($5,685,000);  
   * Room MLE ($8,781,000);  
   * BAE ($5,134,000);  
   * Minimum Exception ($1,272,870 to $3,624,153);
3. [Sign-and-Trade](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/signandtrade/);
4. [Bird Rights](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/#bird) for Prior Team only (if applicable).

If a Player is valued above the NTMLE amount, then his only options are signing with to a Team with sufficient Cap Space or signing with his Prior Team if they have Bird Rights either to stay with his Prior Team or via [Sign-and-Trade](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/signandtrade/) to a new Team.

The following Players are subject to the RFA process:

1. First Round Picks finishing their 4th Year of a [Rookie Scale Contract](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/draftpicks/);
2. Two-Way Players that spent 15 days on an [NBA Roster](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/rosters/) during the Regular Season in the last Season of the Contract;
3. All other Players that have an expiring Contract and have 3 or fewer [YOS](https://cbaguide.com/definitions/#yos) in the League.

**‚úçÔ∏è** For clarity, First Round Picks whose First or Second Year Team Options are not exercised are not RFA‚Äôs despite having 3 or fewer YOS. His Prior Team is limited to signing him to his applicable Rookie Scale Team Option amount (unless Cap Space is available).

### Generally

Along with the QO above, the Team can get right to the point and offer the **Maximum Qualifying Offer** to Players finishing their [Rookie Scale Contracts](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/draftpicks/). This is offered simultaneously with the QO.

### Terms of Maximum QO

The required terms of a Maximum QO are the following:

1. Salary ‚Äì [Maximum Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/contractlimitations/) in Base Compensation (no Bonuses);
2. Increases ‚Äì 8% Increases required;
3. Length ‚Äì 5 Seasons;
4. Protection ‚Äì Full [Compensation Protection](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/) for lack of skill/injury/illness;
5. Options ‚Äì No [Options/ETO‚Äôs](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/options/) permitted.

### Withdrawal and Acceptance

The Maximum QO can only be withdrawn if the standard QO is also withdrawn (i.e. can‚Äôt withdraw the Maximum QO and keep the standard QO).

Player can accept the Maximum QO or the standard QO.

An Offer Sheet must be submitted to the Offering Team by March 1st.

The Offer Sheet must contain the following:

1. Length:  
   * Standard QO ‚Äì Minimum 2 Seasons (exluding Option);  
   * Maximum QO ‚Äì Minimum 3 Seasons if Maximum QO (excluding Option);
2. Two-Way ‚Äì Cannot be for a [Two-Way Contract](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/contracttypes/#twoway);
3. Room ‚Äì The Offering Team must have [Room](https://cbaguide.com/definitions/#room) to sign the Offer Sheet, and retain the Room throughout the entire process.

**üí°** **RFA Process Ties up Team Salary**  
The requirement that the Offering Team have Room throughout the entire RFA process, along with the dates of the RFA process, is the reason why RFA‚Äôs don‚Äôt get many suitors. Teams do not want to tie up Team Salary in an Offer Sheet just to have the Prior Team match, while the Offering Team loses out on other Players in free agency at the same time.

The **Principal Terms** of a Contract are:

1. Term length;
2. [Payment Arrangements](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/paymentarrangements/) (Signing Bonus, Base Compensation, Deferred Compensation and Payment Schedule);
3. [Incentive Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/), limited in the following way:  
   * Team Performance ‚Äì Deemed ‚ÄúLikely‚Äù for both Offering Team and Prior Team;  
   * Bonuses based on League Honors;
4. Any Allowable Amendments (i..e. [Compensation Protection](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/), [Trade Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/tradebonus/), etc.).

**üèÄ** **Utah Makes Guarantees Contingent in Offer Sheet**  
In the 2023 offseason, the Jazz signed 76ers RFA Paul Reed to a 3-year, $23 million Offer Sheet. One savvy term contained in the Offer Sheet was Compensation Protection in Years 2 and 3, conditioned on advancing past the first round of the Playoffs. Because Compensation Protection is a ‚ÄúPrincipal Term‚Äù it‚Äôs a condition the 76ers have to match, and the Jazz knew the 76ers were far more likely to meet the condition than the Jazz at the time. The 76ers still went ahead and matched the Offer Sheet. (the 76ers ended up _not_ advancing in the Playofffs, Reed‚Äôs Contract was therefore non-guaranteed and he was subsequently waived and claimed by Detroit on Waivers).

### Effect After Refusal to Submit to Exam

If the Player fails to submit to a physical within 2 days after the ROFR Notice, the Team can waive the contingency or withdraw the ROFR Notice within 2 days, resulting in the following: 

1. The _Offer Sheet_ is now also deemed invalid and Player can‚Äôt sign with the Offering Team for 1 Year unless Prior Team‚Äôs Matching rights are relinquished (i.e. Player becomes a UFA);
2. Player cannot enter into another Offer Sheet for the current Year;
3. The Qualifying Offer deadline is deemed to have passed (so Player can‚Äôt just sign the QO);
4. Player is prohibited from signing with the Prior Team unless he signed for the Principal Terms from the Offer Sheet within the later of (i) three months from the withdrawal of the ROFR Notice or (ii) January 15th of the current Year;  
   * If the Offer Sheet was made under the Arenas Provision, the Prior Team can still match using the same rules, and make the election with regard to Team Salary should it have sufficient Cap Space to do so.

### Effect of Failed Physical After ROFR Notice

If the Player takes the physical and fails, then the Prior Team can waive the contingency and enter into the Contract, or withdraw the ROFR Notice, at which point the Offering Team and Player are treated as having a signed Contract per the Offer Sheet.

Below is a summary of how the Waiver process works:

1. Team **requests** Waiversfor a Player;
2. Player is on Waivers for 48 hours, when another Team can **claim** his Contract;
3. Player is either claimed (and Contract is assigned to the Claiming Team) or the Contract is terminated and he becomes a UFA;
4. If the Player **clears waivers** (i.e. no one claims him) then he is due any amount of [Protected Compensation](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/) remaining on his Contract, unless a different amount was agreed to in a [Buyout](#buyout).

This page addresses general Trade rules that may apply when executing a Trade. There are separate pages that address the following, more complex Trade topics:

1. [Traded Player Exceptions](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/tpe/);
2. [Trade Salary (Trade Math)](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/salary/);
3. [Trade Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/tradebonus/);
4. [Sign-and-Trade / Extend-and-Trade](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/signandtrade/).

The below circumstances adjust the Player‚Äôs **Outgoing Trade Salary** only:

1. Non-Guaranteed Salary;
2. [Sign-and-Trade](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/trades/signandtrade/) using [Bird Rights](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/#bird).

First the **Total Trade Bonus Amount** must be found. Second, you calculate how it is calculated over the remaining Seasons in the Contract.

**Step 1 ‚Äì Find Total Trade Bonus Amount**

* If Fixed Amount, use that;
* If Percentage-Based:  
   * First, find **Total Base Compensation Owed**;  
         * To find Total Base Compensation Owed, you must find (i) **Current Season Base Compensation Owed** and (ii) **Future Seasons Base Compensation Owed**;  
                  * To find Current Season Base Compensation Owed, you must find **Percent Regular Season Remaining**;  
         * Add Current Season Base Compensation Owed to Future Season Base Compensation Owed to find Total Base Compensation Owed;  
         * Multiply the percentage by the Total Base Compensation Owed to find the Total Trade Bonus Amount.

**Step 2 ‚Äì Allocate Total Trade Bonus Amount** 

* Allocate the Total Trade Bonus Amount as Salary the same way you allocate a [Signing Bonus](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/salary/#signingbonuses).

**Step 3 ‚Äì Adjust Total Trade Bonus Amount and Allocation if it exceeds Maximum Salary**

* Adjust the Salary allocation based on applicable Maximum Salary, which in turn will adjust the Total Trade Bonus Amount.

A Team may execute a Sign-and-Trade with a [Free Agent](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/ufa/) if:

1. Signed prior to the start of the Regular Season;
2. Player is [Free Agent](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/ufa/) and finished prior Season on Sending Team‚Äôs [Roster](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/rosters/);
3. Contract is for at _at least_ 3 Seasons (excluding [Options](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/options/)), up to 4 Seasons;
4. [NTMLE](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/#ntmle) and [Room MLE](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/#room) are not used to sign the Player;
5. First Season of Contract is [fully guaranteed](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensationprotection/);
6. Acquiring Team has sufficient [Room](https://cbaguide.com/definitions/#room) for Player‚Äôs [Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/salary/) plus [Unlikely Bonuses](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/compensation/incentivecompensation/#performance).

Below are the five thresholds in the CBA that carry restrictions and/or penalties, serving to regulate spending and create an even playing field for all Teams:

1. [Minimum Team Salary](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/minimumsalary/);
2. [Salary Cap](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/);
3. [Luxury Tax](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/luxurytax/);
4. [First Apron](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/apron/);
5. [Second Apron](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/apron/).

Because the Salary Cap is a ‚Äúsoft‚Äù Salary Cap (i.e. there are Exceptions permitting Teams to exceed the Salary Cap), the CBA implemented the Luxury Tax to impose financial penalties and the First and Second Aprons to impose roster-building limitations to deter excessive spending.

The Minimum Team Salary threshold, on the other hand, was implemented to ensure Teams were spending a minimum amount on its roster on an annual basis.

When calculating Team Salary, you account for the following. Click the link to jump to the description.

**Include**:

1. [Player Salaries](#salaries);
2. [Waived Salary](#waived);
3. [Retired Players Under Contract](#retired);
4. [Transactions with Retired Players](#retiredtransactions);
5. [Settlements/Grievances](#settlements);
6. [Pending Contracts](#pending);
7. [Outstanding Offer Sheets](#offer);
8. [Cap Holds](#capholds);
9. [Assigned Contracts](#assigned);
10. [Minimum Team Salary Adjusment](#minimum).

**Exclude**:

1. [Renounced Cap Holds](#renouncing);
2. [Long-Term Injury Exclusion](#longterm);
3. [Excludes Contract Types](#contracts).

Cap Holds are a way to artifically add Team Salary as a placeholder for future signings.

It is meant to limit Teams from using all of their cap space to sign new [UFA](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/ufa/)‚Äòs, and then going back and resigning their own Players over the [Salary Cap](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/) using [Bird Rights](https://cbaguide.com/thresholds/salarycap/#bird).

**‚úçÔ∏è** **A Hypothetical to Understand the Purpose of Cap Holds**  
Let‚Äôs say, hypothetically, the Boston Celtics are entering this offseason with Jayson Tatum as a free agent, and the Celtics have $58 million in cap space. This is enough to sign him to his maximum. Without Cap Holds, the Celtics could use the $58 million to sign other Free Agents using cap space, and stay under the Salary Cap threshold. They could then resign Tatum over the Salary Cap using their Bird Rights. The cap holds apply to remove that cap space with the understanding the Celtics are likely going to resign Tatum.

There are four different types of Cap Holds:

1. [Free Agent Cap Holds](#freeagent);
2. [First Round Picks](#pickcaphold);
3. [Open Roster Spots](#open);
4. [Salary Cap Exceptions](#exceptionhold).

A Cap Hold is added to Team Salary for any Player drafted in the First Round by the Team.

### Amount

Apply 120% of the Player‚Äôs [Rookie Scale Amount](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/draftpicks/).

### Date Added

The Cap Hold takes effect immediately upon selection in the [Draft](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/draftrules/).

### Date Removed

The Cap Hold Remains in effect until one of the following occurs:

1. Signs his NBA Contract;
2. Team loses or assigns his [Draft Rights](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/draftrules/);
3. Signs a Non-NBA Contract:  
   * If the Player signs a Non-NBA Contract, the Cap Hold is released on the _later of_ (i) the date he signs the Non-NBA Contract or (ii) the first day of the Regular Season;  
   * The Cap Hold is reinstated on the following July 1st or when the Player is released from the Non-NBA Contract (unless [renounced](#renouncing)). You reapply the same rule above if he signs another Non-NBA Contract after July 1st;
4. Written Letter ‚Äì The Team may remove the Cap Hold prior to the start of the Regular Season by issuing a written statement to the League that the Team will not sign the player during the Salary Cap Year accompanied by a written statement from the Player renouncing his right to accept any Required Tender made by him. The Cap Hold is reinstated on the following July 1st.

A Cap Hold is added to Team Salary for open spots on the [Team Roster](https://cbaguide.com/eligibility/rosters/) to account for the requirement that the Team must sign a Player to fill the roster spot.

### Counting Roster Spots

The following are counted as roster spots for this rule:

1. Players under Contract;
2. Players counting ttoward a [Free Agent Cap Hold](#freeagent);
3. Players counting toward a [Draft Pick Cap Hold](#pickcaphold);
4. Players whom [Offer Sheets](https://cbaguide.com/transactions/signings/rfa/#offersheet) are given.

### Calculating Cap Hold

Once you calculate roster spots, you calculate the potential Cap Hold accordingly:

Calculating Roster Spot Cap Hold

**Step 1** ‚Äì Take total roster spots and subtract it from 12;

**Step 2** ‚Äì If there is a negative number, there is no Open Roster Spot Cap Hold;

**Step 3** ‚Äì If there is a positive number, you multiply that number by the applicable [Minimum Salary](https://cbaguide.com/contractanatomy/terms/contractlimitations/) for a Player with 0 [Years of Service](https://cbaguide.com/definitions/#yos) to determine the Team‚Äôs total Open Roster Spot Cap Hold.

